  <div class="content-tab-panel active" data-tab-panel="logging-overview">
    <p>What matters here is consistency. The log stream tells you which component emitted the line, which method produced it, and which request or event it belongs to, without hiding important state inside interpolated strings.</p>

    <div class="card-grid">
      <div class="card">
        <strong>Delivery</strong>
        <span><code>stderr</code> is the active Docker sink, so <code>docker compose logs</code> shows the same stream the containers emit.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <strong>Correlation</strong>
        <span>Both HTTP services share one <code>request_id</code> through <code>Log::shareContext(...)</code> and return it in <code>X-Request-ID</code>.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <strong>Message Shape</strong>
        <span>Scoped static messages stay grep-friendly. IDs, routing keys, retry counts, and cache flags stay in context.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <strong>Exception Shape</strong>
        <span>Caught throwables are passed as <code>['exception' =&gt; $e]</code>, which keeps Monolog serialization consistent.</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Item</th><th>Value</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Active channel</td><td><code>stderr</code> via Monolog <code>StreamHandler</code></td></tr>
        <tr><td>Default level</td><td><code>debug</code></td></tr>
        <tr><td>Runtime emitters</td><td><code>hr-service</code>, <code>hub-service</code>, <code>hub-consumer</code>, <code>reverb</code></td></tr>
        <tr><td>Fallback channels</td><td><code>stack</code>, <code>single</code>, <code>daily</code>, <code>syslog</code>, <code>errorlog</code>, <code>null</code></td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="content-tab-panel" data-tab-panel="logging-inventory">
    <p>The log surface is intentionally small: 30 application log call sites in total. That count excludes console output such as <code>$this-&gt;info(...)</code> and the two <code>Log::shareContext(...)</code> registrations.</p>

    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Scope</th><th>Levels</th><th>Typical messages</th><th>Main context</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Cross-cutting</td>
          <td><code>warning</code>, <code>error</code></td>
          <td><code>Request metrics recording failed</code>, <code>Unhandled exception</code></td>
          <td><code>request_id</code>, <code>method</code>, <code>endpoint</code>, <code>status</code>, <code>exception</code></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>HR write side</td>
          <td><code>info</code>, <code>error</code></td>
          <td><code>Employee created</code>, <code>Employee updated</code>, <code>Employee deleted</code>, <code>Event published</code>, <code>Failed to publish event</code></td>
          <td><code>employee_id</code>, <code>country</code>, <code>changed_fields</code>, <code>routing_key</code>, <code>event_id</code>, <code>exception</code></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Hub read side</td>
          <td><code>debug</code>, <code>warning</code></td>
          <td><code>Employee list served</code>, <code>Checklist served</code>, <code>Hub service health check degraded</code>, <code>Consistency check failed</code></td>
          <td><code>country</code>, paging fields, cache hit flags, <code>checks</code>, totals</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Hub event pipeline</td>
          <td><code>info</code>, <code>warning</code>, <code>error</code></td>
          <td><code>Duplicate event skipped</code>, <code>Dispatching event to handler</code>, <code>No handler found for event</code>, <code>Broadcast sent via Reverb</code>, <code>Failed to process RabbitMQ message</code>, <code>Message exhausted retries; routing to DLQ</code></td>
          <td><code>event_type</code>, <code>event_id</code>, <code>employee_id</code>, <code>country</code>, <code>retry_count</code>, <code>duration_ms</code>, <code>exception</code></td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="content-tab-panel" data-tab-panel="logging-traces">
    <div class="pattern-grid">
      <article class="pattern-card">
        <div class="pattern-card-head">
          <div class="pattern-card-title">
            <span class="pattern-badge">Success Path</span>
            <h3>Employee write to live update</h3>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p>A normal event passes through the write API, RabbitMQ, the Hub projection pipeline, and Reverb without changing message shape.</p>
        <div class="pattern-steps">
          <div class="pattern-step">
            <div class="pattern-step-index">1</div>
            <div class="pattern-step-body"><strong>HR write</strong><span>The controller logs the mutation with <code>employee_id</code>, <code>country</code>, and the shared <code>request_id</code>.</span></div>
          </div>
          <div class="pattern-step">
            <div class="pattern-step-index">2</div>
            <div class="pattern-step-body"><strong>Broker publish</strong><span>The publisher logs the routing key and event ID after RabbitMQ accepts the message.</span></div>
          </div>
          <div class="pattern-step">
            <div class="pattern-step-index">3</div>
            <div class="pattern-step-body"><strong>Projection dispatch</strong><span>The Hub pipeline records handler dispatch and preserves <code>event_id</code>, <code>event_type</code>, and <code>country</code>.</span></div>
          </div>
          <div class="pattern-step">
            <div class="pattern-step-index">4</div>
            <div class="pattern-step-body"><strong>Broadcast complete</strong><span>The consumer logs the broadcast and the final processing duration once the event is fully applied.</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="pattern-card">
        <div class="pattern-card-head">
          <div class="pattern-card-title">
            <span class="pattern-badge">Failure Path</span>
            <h3>Retry and dead-letter flow</h3>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p>Failures stay visible without losing structure. The error line keeps the exception object in context, and the retry lines carry the backoff state.</p>
        <div class="pattern-steps">
          <div class="pattern-step">
            <div class="pattern-step-index">1</div>
            <div class="pattern-step-body"><strong>Processing failure</strong><span>The consumer emits one scoped error line with <code>event_type</code>, <code>retry_count</code>, and <code>exception</code>.</span></div>
          </div>
          <div class="pattern-step">
            <div class="pattern-step-index">2</div>
            <div class="pattern-step-body"><strong>Backoff</strong><span><code>requeueWithDelay()</code> logs the next retry count and the computed delay in milliseconds.</span></div>
          </div>
          <div class="pattern-step">
            <div class="pattern-step-index">3</div>
            <div class="pattern-step-body"><strong>Final attempt</strong><span>The same message shape is reused through every retry, which makes multi-attempt traces easy to grep.</span></div>
          </div>
          <div class="pattern-step">
            <div class="pattern-step-index">4</div>
            <div class="pattern-step-body"><strong>DLQ handoff</strong><span>Once retries are exhausted, the consumer logs the dead-letter decision as a warning before the message is nacked.</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>

    <div class="terminal-block">
<span class="t-gray"># Successful event</span>
[INFO] [EmployeeController][store] Employee created {"employee_id":1,"country":"USA","request_id":"abc-123"}
[INFO] [RabbitMQPublisher][publish] Event published {"routing_key":"employee.created.usa","event_id":"evt-456","request_id":"abc-123"}
[INFO] [EventProcessingPipeline][process] Dispatching event to handler {"handler":"App\\Application\\EventProcessing\\Handlers\\EmployeeCreatedHandler","event_type":"EmployeeCreated","event_id":"evt-456","country":"USA"}
[INFO] [EmployeeCreatedHandler][handle] Employee created event handled {"employee_id":1,"country":"USA"}
[INFO] [RabbitMQConsumer][processMessage] Broadcast sent via Reverb {"event_type":"EmployeeCreated","employee_id":1,"country":"USA","channels":["employees","country.USA"]}
[INFO] [RabbitMQConsumer][processMessage] Event fully processed {"event_type":"EmployeeCreated","employee_id":1,"country":"USA","duration_ms":45.12,"retry_count":0}

<span class="t-gray"># Failed event</span>
[ERROR] [RabbitMQConsumer][processMessage] Failed to process RabbitMQ message {"event_type":"EmployeeCreated","retry_count":0,"exception":"&lt;normalized Throwable&gt;"}
[INFO] [RabbitMQConsumer][requeueWithDelay] Message re-queued for retry {"retry_count":1,"delay_ms":1000}
[ERROR] [RabbitMQConsumer][processMessage] Failed to process RabbitMQ message {"event_type":"EmployeeCreated","retry_count":3,"exception":"&lt;normalized Throwable&gt;"}
[WARNING] [RabbitMQConsumer][processMessage] Message exhausted retries; routing to DLQ {"event_type":"EmployeeCreated","retry_count":3}
    </div>

    <p class="log-meta">The consumer log currently records <code>employees</code> and <code>country.{country}</code> in its <code>channels</code> field. The broadcast event itself also fans out to <code>checklist.{country}</code>.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="content-tab-panel" data-tab-panel="logging-commands">
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Command</th><th>Use</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><code>docker compose logs hr-service</code></td><td>HR API writes and publish flow</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>docker compose logs hub-service</code></td><td>Hub read endpoints and health</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>docker compose logs hub-consumer</code></td><td>Event processing, broadcast, retries, and DLQ flow</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>docker compose logs reverb</code></td><td>WebSocket server activity</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>docker compose logs -f --tail=40 hr-service hub-consumer reverb rabbitmq</code></td><td>Common live view across the moving parts</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>docker compose logs -f</code></td><td>Full live stream</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>docker compose logs hub-consumer 2&gt;&amp;1 | grep '\[RabbitMQConsumer\]'</code></td><td>Consumer-only lines</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>docker compose logs hub-consumer 2&gt;&amp;1 | grep '"event_id"'</code></td><td>Trace one event through the pipeline</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <div class="callout callout-success">
      For demos and local debugging, <code>docker compose logs -f --tail=40 hr-service hub-consumer reverb rabbitmq</code> is the most useful default view: enough history to catch the last event, but not so much noise that retries and broadcasts disappear off screen.
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
